Package homeworks.hw1

Class MyStack<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • homeworks.hw1.MyStack<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<T>
    public class MyStack<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Iterable<T>
    MyStack is a simple class that implements a stack abstraction. To help debug the class and demonstrate how fail-fast Iterators should work, this class is made Iterable. MyStack instances are created with a maximum capacity which is provided at construction time. If pushes are made that would exceed this capacity, an instance of StackOverflowError is thrown.

      • iterator

        public java.util.Iterator<T> iterator()
        Returns a smart pointer over elements of type T. You should think about how you can implement this Iterator to:
        1. Access the elements in so-called proper order, which is fancy speak for " the order that the data structure implies by its semantics ". For a stack, proper order means LIFO, since when imagining a stack, we want the most recently pushed element to be accessed first, the second most recent one accessed second, etc. For a priority queue, proper order would mean from smaller to greater priority, with tie-breakers broken by insertion order (FIFO).
        2. Make it fail-fast. After you do this, you will probably also want to implement a fail-safe Iterator so that you can answer your homework effectively. Can you see for yourself how complex the behavior and implementation of such a Iterator can be?
        Specified by:
        iterator in interface java.lang.Iterable<T>
        Returns:
        An Iterator instance.
        See Also:
        ConcurrentModificationException, IllegalStateException, NoSuchElementException
